Introduction to Helm

Before Helm

Suppose you want to deploy a Spring Boot application to Kubernetes.

You would need to create several YAML files like

deployment.yaml, service.yaml, configmap.yaml,secret.yaml,ingress.yaml,hpa.yaml,pvc.yaml,networkpolicy.yaml

For a single application, it's common to have 8 to 15 YAML files.

Now imagine you have:

Dev environment
QA environment
Stage environment
Production environment

You would either:

Maintain separate copies of these YAMLs, or Edit values manually for each environment.

This becomes difficult to manage.

Problems Without Helm

Suppose your application image changes.

Old image: myapp:v1

New image: myapp:v2

You must update every Deployment YAML that references the image.

If you also need to change:

Replica count
Namespace
Service type
Ingress host
Resource limits

those changes have to be repeated in multiple places. This is time-consuming and increases the chance of mistakes.

Helm Solves This Problem

Helm lets you create a template with variables.

Example:

image:
  repository: myapp
  tag: v2

replicaCount: 3

Instead of hardcoding values in every YAML, Helm substitutes these values when it generates the Kubernetes manifests.

